    "description": "Nagina Wood Craft Nagina Wood Craft, known for its intricate carving and inlay work, received its GI tag in 2023. The craft originates from Nagina, a small town in the Bijnor district of Uttar Pradesh. The tradition dates back to the Mughal era, with some wood carvers believed to have moved from Iran to Uttar Pradesh. The craft specializes in carving on ebony and sheesham wood, often featuring intricate designs and motifs.",
    "history": "Nagina's wood-carving tradition traces its origin to the Mughal era when Persian craftsmen, accompanying Mughal nobles to the Rohilkhand region, settled in Nagina and passed on their carving and inlay skills. Over centuries, local artisans adapted Persian motifs to Indian sensibilities, creating a distinctive Nagina style.",
    "uniqueness": "Nagina Wood Craft specialises in fine carving and inlay on ebony (shisham) and rosewood, featuring intricate Persian-influenced floral and geometric designs. The use of dark-toned hardwoods allows for sharper contrast in carved details and inlay work that is characteristic of this tradition.",
    "makingProcess": "Seasoned ebony or sheesham wood is cut to shape and the design is transferred using a carbon stencil. Artisans use fine chisels to carve the surface, creating recesses for inlay materials such as brass wire, silver, or contrasting wood. Inlay pieces are pressed into the recesses with adhesive, then the whole surface is sanded flush and polished to a high sheen.",
