    "history": "Gaura stone craft in Mahoba has roots in the Chandela dynasty era (9th–13th century), when the Bundelkhand region was known for its stone temple architecture. Local artisans who worked on the region's famous Khajuraho and Mahoba temples developed expertise in working with Gaura stone, passing the craft down through generations.",
    "uniqueness": "Gaura stone (Pyro Flight Stone or Pyrophyllite) found in the Mahoba region is uniquely soft when freshly extracted, allowing artisans to carve extraordinarily fine details. It hardens progressively upon air exposure, making it exceptionally durable once the carving is complete.",
    "makingProcess": "Freshly extracted Gaura stone blocks are shaped with saws and chisels while still relatively soft. Artisans carve decorative motifs, figurines, and utility items using fine chisels and rasps. The carved piece is smoothed with abrasive stones and left to air-harden for several weeks before being polished with sandpaper to reveal its natural white luster.",
