    "description": "Muzaffarnagar Gur, also known as Muzaffarnagar Jaggery, received its GI tag on March 31, 2023. This traditional non-centrifugal cane sugar is made from fresh sugarcane juice and is known for its unique flavor and quality. The geographical area covered includes Muzaffarnagar district and nearby areas like Bijnor, Shamli, Baghpat, Meerut, and Shajahanpur in Uttar Pradesh.",
    "history": "Jaggery-making in Muzaffarnagar has a history of several centuries, rooted in the fertile sugarcane fields of the Ganga-Yamuna Doab. The region's ideal combination of alluvial soil, moderate climate, and water availability produces sugarcane with exceptionally high sucrose content, making Muzaffarnagar gur sought after across northern India.",
    "uniqueness": "Muzaffarnagar Gur is made from a single pressing of fresh sugarcane juice without centrifugation, preserving natural minerals, vitamins, and molasses content. It has a distinctive deep amber color, earthy sweetness, and long shelf life compared to refined sugar, making it unique among Indian jaggery varieties.",
    "makingProcess": "Freshly cut sugarcane is crushed in traditional mills (kolhu) to extract juice, which is collected in large iron pans. The juice is clarified with natural coagulants, then boiled over wood fires while being stirred constantly to concentrate it. When the correct consistency is reached, it is poured into moulds and allowed to cool and solidify into traditional block or cone forms.",
