    "description": "Jalesar Dhatu Shilp Jalesar Dhatu Shilp, also known as Jalesar Metal Craft, is an intricate metalworking tradition originating from Jalesar town in Etah district of Uttar Pradesh. The craft received its GI tag on August 1, 2023. Known for its exquisite brassware and decorative items, particularly ghungroos (anklets) and ghantis (bells), this craft showcases the region's rich metalworking heritage. Over 1,200 small units in the area are engaged in producing these fine metal crafts. The geographical area covered includes Jalesar town and surrounding areas in Etah district, Uttar Pradesh.",
    "history": "Jalesar in Etah district has been known as the \"City of Bells\" for several centuries, with artisan families specialising in casting ghungroos (ankle bells) and other metal bells for temples and classical dancers across India. The craft grew under the patronage of Rajput and Mughal courts that valued high-quality musical instruments.",
    "uniqueness": "Jalesar produces an estimated 80–90% of India's ghungroos (ankle bells used in Bharatanatyam, Kathak, and other classical dances) as well as temple bells of all sizes. The specific alloy composition and casting technique used by Jalesar craftsmen gives these bells their distinctive clear, sustained tone.",
    "makingProcess": "A specific bell-metal alloy (typically copper with tin) is melted and cast in small clay or sand moulds shaped for ghungroos or temple bells. After casting, the rough bells are trimmed and filed, then the interior is fitted with a small metal pellet (the clapper for ghungroos) or left hollow for temple bells. Bells are tested for tone quality before polishing.",
