    "description": "received its GI tag Pilibhit is known as \"Bansuri Nagari\" – the land of flutes, for producing and exporting roughly 95% of India's flutes. The geographical area covered includes Pilibhit district of Uttar Pradesh.",
    "history": "Flute-making in Pilibhit developed over more than a century, taking root when local craftsmen began working with the reed bamboo (Dendrocalamus strictus) found abundantly in the Terai forests at the foot of the Himalayas. As generations of craftsmen refined the bore dimensions and hole placements, Pilibhit emerged as the single largest supplier of flutes in India.",
    "uniqueness": "Pilibhit accounts for approximately 95% of India's total flute production, with its bansuris prized by professional classical musicians for their precise tonal accuracy, even bore, and consistent pitch across registers. The specific Terai bamboo used has a natural wall thickness and density that produces superior resonance compared to bamboo from other regions.",
    "makingProcess": "Sections of seasoned Terai reed bamboo (Dendrocalamus strictus) are cut to precise lengths determined by the desired pitch. The inner bore is cleaned and smoothed with metal rods. Finger holes are drilled at acoustically calculated intervals using traditional gauges. The mouth hole is beveled with a special cutter and the flute is tested, tuned by micro-adjustments to the holes, and finished with a natural beeswax seal at the nodes.",
    "materials": [],
    "artisanName": "Raies Ahmed",
    "challenges": "Before receiving the GI tag, Pilibhit Bansuri struggled with inadequate recognition of its unique craftsmanship and cultural significance, even within India.",
    "nabardSupport": "NABARD has provided support for GI registration of products, including Pilibhit Bansuri. They offer end-to-end support in facilitating pre-registration and post-registration activities for GI products.",
    "impact": "The GI tag has helped preserve the authenticity of Pilibhit Bansuri and improved recognition for genuine products. It contributes to protecting the livelihoods of traditional flute makers and maintaining the cultural heritage of the region."
