    "description": ", also known as Dhalua Murti Metal Casting Craft, received its GI tag on April 16, 2024. This traditional craft originates from the Kashipura locality of Varanasi and is renowned for its intricate metal idols. The geographical area covered includes Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh.",
    "history": "Metal idol casting in Varanasi has been practiced for centuries in the Kashipura locality, where communities of Kasyara (metal casters) have supplied brass and panchdhatu (five-metal alloy) idols to temples and households across India. The tradition uses techniques documented in ancient Sanskrit texts on idol making (pratima lakshana).",
    "uniqueness": "The Banaras Metal Casting craft (Dhalua Murti) uses the lost-wax (cire perdue) casting method as well as sand casting to produce intricate metal idols following precise iconographic specifications. The panchdhatu alloy — a mixture of gold, silver, copper, iron, and tin — is considered sacred and uniquely suited for divine images.",
    "makingProcess": "A wax model of the deity is sculpted following traditional iconographic proportions. It is encased in a clay mould with a pouring channel, dried, and heated so the wax melts out. Molten brass or panchdhatu is poured into the cavity and the mould is broken after cooling. The rough casting is then chased, detailed with fine tools, and polished to achieve the finished idol.",
