    "history": "Kathiya wheat is an ancient indigenous variety cultivated in the Bundelkhand region for generations, adapted over centuries to the region's semi-arid, drought-prone climate. It is one of the few heritage wheat varieties that survived the Green Revolution's emphasis on high-yielding modern varieties, preserved by traditional farmers.",
    "uniqueness": "Bundelkhand Kathiya Gehu is a heritage wheat variety with naturally high protein content, a robust gluten structure, and the ability to thrive in harsh conditions with minimal water. Unlike modern wheat varieties, Kathiya is well-adapted to the black cotton soils of Bundelkhand and requires no chemical inputs under traditional farming.",
    "makingProcess": "Kathiya wheat is sown directly in the black cotton soils of Bundelkhand in October-November using traditional broadcast or seed drill methods. It grows on residual soil moisture with minimal irrigation. The crop is harvested by hand with sickles in March-April, threshed using traditional methods, and the grain is cleaned and stored in clay vessels or milled into flour for local consumption.",
