    "auCount": 0,
    "description": "Banaras lal Bharwa Mirch Banaras Lal Bharwa mirch is one of the most valuable crops grown in north eastern region. Fruits are long or small with high pungency. It is used as a principal ingredient of various curries and chutneys. It is also used for vegetables, spices, condiments, sauces and pickles. Banaras Lal Bharwamirch is good sources of vitamin A and vitamin C. Cultivars. local cultivars prefers this variety for this region. The specialty of this red Bharva chilly is when it is on the field, the skin is very thick and when this chilly has used after stuffing the spices for making stuff pickle (Bharwa Achar) then gradually the chilly skin has thinner and thinner like a thin paper.",
    "history": "Bharwamirch (stuffed and sun-dried chilli) is a centuries-old preservation and culinary tradition of Varanasi, developed to make seasonal chillies available year-round. The Lal (red) variety — large, thick-walled chillies grown in the Varanasi region — became the preferred base for this condiment, prized in the Banarasi kitchen.",
    "uniqueness": "Banaras Lal Bharwamirch uses a specific thick-walled red chilli variety grown in the Varanasi region, stuffed with a proprietary blend of local spices (mustard, fennel, asafoetida, dried mango powder) and sun-dried. The combination of regional chilli variety and the specific spice blend creates a condiment with a distinctive tangy-spicy-umami flavour unique to Varanasi.",
    "makingProcess": "Large red chillies are slit lengthwise without cutting through. A prepared spice mixture — including mustard seeds, fennel, asafoetida, dried mango powder, and salt — is packed tightly into the slit chilli. The stuffed chillies are smeared with mustard oil and spread on flat surfaces in direct sunlight for 5–7 days until completely dehydrated and preserved.",
