    "description": ", a beloved local sweetmeat from Varanasi, received its GI tag on March 30, 2024. Known for its distinctive brown-red color and unique taste, this heat-desiccated milk product is made from a blend of cow and buffalo milk. The geographical area covered includes Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh.",
    "history": "Lal Peda is a beloved sweetmeat of Varanasi with a history spanning at least 150–200 years in the city's mithai (sweet) tradition. The recipe was developed by Banarasi halwais (confectioners) who perfected the slow reduction of cow and buffalo milk to create a caramelized sweet with a distinctive reddish-brown colour unique to this region.",
    "uniqueness": "Banaras Lal Peda is distinguished from other peda varieties by its deep brown-red caramelized color, achieved through prolonged slow cooking of a blend of cow and buffalo milk. The mixing of both milk types, combined with the specific degree of caramelization, creates a flavour complexity — simultaneously sweet, slightly smoky, and milky — that cannot be replicated with cow milk or buffalo milk alone.",
    "makingProcess": "Equal proportions of cow and buffalo milk are combined in a wide, heavy-bottomed iron pan (karahi) and cooked over a low wood or gas flame for several hours, stirred continuously. The mixture is reduced and caramelized until it turns a deep reddish-brown and achieves a firm, malleable consistency. It is then shaped into flat, round pedas and allowed to cool and set.",
