    "auCount": 0,
    "description": "Karonda is a medium sized, thorny shrub and the fruit is globose berry. It appears from March to August and ripens between May and December. Immature fruits are green in colour and turn to white to reddish purple at maturity. These are round to oblong, sweet, though slightly acidic, juice when fully ripe. Karonda wood is hard, straight-grained and use for firewood purpose. The green plant serves as a protective hedge around agricultural holdings. Chiraigaon Karonda of district Varanasi is unique, superior and attractive maroon coloured fruit. The fruit weight was higher (10 g) with less no. of seeds fruit-1 (3) with excellent blend of TSS (9.5 B) and acidity (1.10). Higher vitamin C (28 mg 100 g-1) content with attractive maroon coloured fruits. b. Registration Holder: : Naarikisan Kashi Producer Company Limited c.Location: Chiraigaon ,Varanasi",
    "history": "Karonda (Carissa carandas) cultivation in the Chiraigaon area of Varanasi has been practiced for generations, with local farmers developing expertise in growing this thorny shrub in the specific riverine and alluvial conditions of the Ganga flood plain. The berry is deeply embedded in local culinary and medicinal traditions.",
    "uniqueness": "Chiraigaon Karonda is distinguished by its specific growing conditions — the alluvial soil and microclimate of the Chiraigaon area of Varanasi — which produce berries with a characteristic sharp tartness, deep purple-red colour at full ripeness, and high levels of iron and vitamin C. These properties are consistently linked to this specific geography.",
    "makingProcess": "Karonda shrubs are cultivated in well-drained alluvial soil with minimal inputs. Berries are harvested by hand twice a year — once in early summer when they are green and tart, and once in late monsoon when ripe and dark red. They are used fresh in chutneys and curries, or processed by sun-drying or preservation in brine and oil to make pickles.",
