    "description": "Banarasi Tabla received its GI tag on March 30, 2024. This percussion instrument is renowned for its unique craftsmanship and sound quality. The geographical area covered includes Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh. Banarasi Tabla is known for its distinctive tonal quality and is an integral part of Indian classical music.",
    "history": "Tabla-making in Varanasi is a centuries-old tradition inextricably linked to the city's position as the capital of Hindustani classical music. Master instrument makers (ustads) developed the specific dimensions and tuning compositions of the Banaras baj (style) tabla, which differs in tonal character from the Delhi and Punjab school tables.",
    "uniqueness": "Banarasi Tabla is distinguished by its specific syahi (black tuning paste) composition and the dimensions of the dayan (treble drum) and bayan (bass drum), which produce the characteristic deep, resonant tone associated with the Banaras gharana. Master craftsmen in Varanasi are the custodians of these specifications.",
    "makingProcess": "The dayan (treble drum) is turned from a single piece of seasoned rosewood or sheesham on a lathe. Goat skin is stretched over the wooden body through a system of rawhide lacing and wooden pegs. Syahi — a paste of iron filings, rice starch, and charcoal — is applied in concentric layers to the centre of the dayan head, carefully tuned by tapping and adjusting. The bayan (bass drum) is cast from brass and fitted with a buffalo-skin head.",
