    "history": "The Shehnai has been crafted and played in Varanasi for centuries, traditionally associated with temple music, wedding processions, and royal court entertainment. The instrument reached its highest artistic recognition through Ustad Bismillah Khan, who performed Shehnai at India's first Independence Day at Red Fort in 1947, forever associating the instrument with Varanasi.",
    "uniqueness": "The Banarasi Shehnai is distinguished by its specific bore taper, the quality of its double reed (made from a local aquatic grass grown in the Ganga flood plains), and the tonal warmth achieved by Varanasi craftsmen through precise wood selection and interior finishing. These specifications produce a sound distinct from shehnais made elsewhere.",
    "makingProcess": "The body of the Shehnai is turned on a lathe from sheesham or tun wood, bored to a precise conical taper with a metal-tipped rod. A brass or bell-metal flared bell (nali) is attached to the lower end. The double reed is carefully crafted from pati grass (Arundo donax) grown in the Ganga flood plains: two thin grass sections are bound together with thread and shaped to produce the desired pitch when inserted into the top of the instrument.",
