    "nabardSupported": "18.10.2021",
    "proprietor": "Human Social Welfare Society",
    "facilitator": "Human Welfare Association, Varanasi",
    "auCount": 0,
    "description": "The word \"Sanjhi\" comes from the Hindi term \"Sandhya\" that means dusk – the time when cows return home. It is considered the most sacred time for the ritual. According to the Srimad bhagwatam, Radharani herself initiated the practice of Sanjhi by creating such designs with the fellow Gopis. Reinventing Sanjhi art, a unique form of paper craft.\"Sanjhi craft\". Originated from Mathura, India; it is a truly unique craft that features exquisite designs and motifs cut on paper. Coming from Lord Krishna\"s hometown Mathura, Sanjhi art began as a form of traditional stenciling. Beginning in the 16th century, these stencils were used to decorate the walls and floors of temples with motifs. \" Agency name : Human Social Welfare Society",
    "history": "Sanjhi art has been practiced in Mathura and the Braj region for over 500 years, rooted in the Vaishnava devotional tradition. The art form is associated with the Sanjhi festival celebrated in temples in honour of Goddess Parvati, where intricate paper-cut and rangoli designs depicting scenes from Krishna's life are created daily during the Sharad season.",
    "uniqueness": "Mathura Sanjhi Craft is unique in its combination of fine paper-cutting (kaaghaz katai) and coloured powder (rangoli) application, used to create large, intricate floor and wall compositions in temple courtyards. The designs — featuring peacocks, lotus flowers, and scenes from the Ramayana and Mahabharata — follow an iconographic tradition specific to the Braj devotional schools.",
    "makingProcess": "Artisans cut intricate stencil designs from thin paper using fine scissors and small knives, creating detailed lacework patterns. These stencils are placed on a flat surface and coloured powders (dried flower petals, mineral colours, or synthetic pigments) are pressed through the cut-outs to create the rangoli design. Temple Sanjhi compositions can span several square metres and are created daily during the festival season.",
    "materials": [],
    "artisanName": "Local Artisans",
    "challenges": "Before GI registration, Mathura Sanjhi Craft faced issues such as lack of recognition for their unique craftsmanship and competition from mass-produced items.",
