    "description": "received its GI tag in 2023. This traditional craft originates from Chitrakoot district in Uttar Pradesh. The region is known for its abundance of wood due to being a forest area, which serves as the raw material for the craft. Craftsmen in Chitrakoot are skilled in creating a wide range of wooden products, including toys, furniture, and building materials like door and window frames.",
    "history": "The wooden craft tradition of Chitrakoot is rooted in the region's dense forest heritage and its deep association with the Ramayana. Lord Ram is believed to have spent a significant part of his 14-year exile in Chitrakoot, making the region sacred and a pilgrimage destination. Local craftsmen developed the tradition of carving religious artifacts and toys for pilgrims visiting the area.",
    "uniqueness": "Chitrakoot wooden craft draws on locally available forest timber — including teak, mahua, and sal — to produce toys, religious figures, furniture, and architectural elements. The craft is distinguished by its incorporation of Ramayana-themed carvings and motifs, reflecting the region's unique spiritual identity and making Chitrakoot pieces instantly recognisable.",
    "makingProcess": "Seasoned hardwood from local forests is cut to size and the design is marked on the surface. Artisans use chisels, gouges, and hand saws to shape and carve the wood into toys, figurines, or furniture components. Intricate decorative elements are added with fine carving tools. Finished pieces are sanded smooth and treated with natural oils or lacquer for durability.",
