    "description": "Varanasi fairs high on the production of milk and curd and thus a profound use of these items can be found in most of the city's preparations. Banarasi Thandai is famous across India for its refreshing taste and celebratory spirit. Thandai is a popular and refreshing Banarsi drink prepared on the regular basis, each and every day available to drink in the hundreds of Thandai shops in the Varanasi, but it is much popular at the time of festivals like Holi and Mahashivratri. Made from seasonal fruit puree, Thandai is served in a kulhad topped with Rabri and flavoured with rose essence, ice- cream, dry fruits and nuts. Condiments like fennel seeds, magaztari seeds, pepper, vetiver seeds, cardamom and saffron make the flavours truly rich and refreshing.",
    "history": "Thandai has been a cultural staple of Varanasi for several centuries, deeply associated with the festivals of Holi and Mahashivratri when it is consumed in large quantities as a cooling, celebratory drink. The recipe was refined by Banarasi confectioners (halwais) who developed the specific spice blend that gives Banaras Thandai its distinctive character.",
    "uniqueness": "Banaras Thandai is distinguished from thandai made elsewhere by its specific formulation: a precise blend of blanched almonds, fennel seeds, cardamom, rose petals, white pepper, melon seeds, and poppy seeds, all ground fresh daily and mixed with full-fat milk. The overnight soaking and stone-grinding of ingredients creates a depth of flavour that instant versions cannot replicate.",
    "makingProcess": "Almonds, fennel seeds, cardamom pods, dried rose petals, white peppercorns, melon seeds, and poppy seeds are soaked overnight in water. The next day, each ingredient is ground separately on a stone grinder (silbatta) or blender to a very fine paste. The combined paste is mixed into chilled, full-fat milk, sweetened with sugar, and strained through muslin to remove fibres before serving cold.",
