    "description": "Banaras has a treasure full of variety of art & craft but the Mural painting of this holy city is quite notable among all. The Banaras Mural painting has a connection with every segment of Banarasi society and reflects the culture, tradition and the history of the city. There are different categories of Banaras Mural Painting as such: Important temples for wall paintings, Subjects of the paintings and Representation of different states in the temples of Banaras. Banaras has an age-old tradition of Banaras Mural Painting on the walls of the house, temples, Dharmshalas and many other important places. Walls and facades of the buildings are decorated with vibrant murals made by local artists in the folk painting style. Every aspect of the nature, human life, mythology, flora & fauna are used as a subject of Banaras Mural Painting. This mural art of Banaras is an extended folk form of the Classical art.",
    "history": "Banaras has an age-old tradition of mural painting on the walls of temples, dharamshalas, and homes, with documented examples going back several centuries. The tradition developed as an extended folk form of classical Indian painting, with local artists creating vibrant compositions on architectural surfaces using mineral pigments and natural colours.",
    "uniqueness": "Banaras Mural Painting uniquely blends folk and classical painting traditions, depicting a wide range of subjects — mythology, flora and fauna, daily life, and cultural celebrations — in a bold, expressive style specific to the Kashi (Varanasi) tradition. The use of earthy mineral pigments mixed with lime gives the murals remarkable durability and a distinctive tonality.",
    "makingProcess": "Wall surfaces are prepared with a base coat of lime plaster mixed with natural binders. Artisans sketch the composition directly on the prepared surface with charcoal or chalk. Colours are prepared from mineral pigments, natural earths, and vegetable dyes mixed with lime water or natural binders. The painting is applied in layers from background to foreground, with fine details added last using thin brushes.",
