    "description": "Meerut Bugle The Meerut Bigul, or Meerut Brass Bugle, is crafted primarily from high-quality brass sourced locally. Skilled artisans meticulously shape and assemble the bugle, incorporating intricate designs and engravings. Its uniqueness lies in its rich, resonant sound that carries far distances, making it an indispensable instrument for military bands, ceremonial events, and religious processions.",
    "history": "Meerut's tradition of making brass bugles and military band instruments developed significantly during the British colonial era when the city became one of India's most important military cantonments. The Indian Army's demand for high-quality bugles and band instruments established Meerut as the primary manufacturing centre for these instruments, a role it continues to hold.",
    "uniqueness": "Meerut Bugles are made from high-quality local brass with precise bore dimensions perfected through generations of military instrument-making. Their distinctive rich, resonant tone — which carries long distances — is achieved through the specific alloy composition (70:30 copper-zinc) and the hand-hammered bell construction that Meerut craftsmen have refined over more than a century.",
    "makingProcess": "Brass sheet is cut and shaped into tubing by rolling on mandrels and soldering the seam. The tubing is bent into the bugle's characteristic loop shape using internal sand-packing to prevent kinking. The bell is spun and flared on a lathe. All components are assembled by hard-soldering, checked for air-tightness, and the bore is refined with a mandrel. The finished bugle is polished, lacquered, and the sound tested by the craftsman.",
